\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
(Exercise 3.11)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Solution.
 
\series default
We can write the Lagrangian os this systems in terms of the coordinates
 of the center of mass and the coordinates of the particles relative to
 the them(center of mass), moreover, when we do that, we obtaing cyclic
 coordinates for the center of mass, then, we can represent the system with
 just the coordinates of the particles relative to the CM.
 Now, having said that, if we choose polar coordinates as generalized coordintat
es, we have that the lagrangian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{\mu}{2}\left(\dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}\right)+\frac{k}{r},
\]

\end_inset

where the last term comes from the fact that we're dealing with gravitational
 forces and also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 represents the reduced mass, which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=\frac{m_{1}m_{2}}{m_{1}+m_{2}},
\]

\end_inset

thus, with this information, we know that the angular momentum is conserved,
 i.e 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\theta}=\frac{l}{\mu r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and we also have the radial equation as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu r\dot{\theta}^{2}-\frac{k}{r^{2}}-\mu\ddot{r}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iff\mu\ddot{r}=\mu r\dot{\theta}^{2}-\frac{k}{r^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

and we can interpret the rhs of the previous equation as an effective potential,
 but we know that in order to have circular orbits, this effective force
 must be zero, so, if we assume that the radius is 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu r_{0}\dot{\theta}^{2}-\frac{k}{r_{0}^{2}}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iff\mu r_{0}^{3}\dot{\theta}^{2}=k\iff r_{0}=\left(\frac{k}{\mu\dot{\theta}^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}},
\]

\end_inset

on the other hand, we know that the preiod is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\frac{2\pi}{\dot{\theta}},
\]

\end_inset

then we can rewrite the condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{0}=\left(\frac{k\tau^{2}}{4\pi^{2}\mu}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}.
\]

\end_inset

Now, when the particles are stopped, then, the equation for the radial component
 ends up being 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{k}{r^{2}}-\mu\ddot{r}=0\iff\mu\ddot{r}=-\frac{k}{r^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

and now, let's solve that differential equation, and in order to achieve
 that, let's multiply it by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\dot{r}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\mu\dot{r}\ddot{r}=-\frac{2k}{r^{2}}\dot{r}\implies2\dot{r}\ddot{r}=-\frac{2k}{\mu r^{2}}\dot{r}
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\dot{r}\ddot{r}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\dot{r}^{2}\right),\hspace{1em}-\frac{2k\dot{r}}{\mu r^{2}}=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{2k}{\mu r}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\left(\dot{r}^{2}\right)=\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{2k}{\mu r}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\left(\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{2k}{\mu r}\right)=0\implies\dot{r}^{2}=\frac{2k}{\mu r}+\alpha,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a constant of integration, which says that the radial velocity is zero
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}$
\end_inset

, and if we choose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=-\frac{2k}{\mu r_{0}},
\]

\end_inset

then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}^{2}=\frac{2k}{\mu r}+\frac{2k}{\mu r_{0}}=\frac{2k}{\mu}\left(\frac{1}{r}-\frac{1}{r_{0}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{r}^{2}=\frac{2k}{\mu}\left(\frac{1}{r}-\frac{1}{r_{0}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{r}=\sqrt{\frac{2k}{\mu}}\sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{r}-\frac{1}{r_{0}}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}=\sqrt{\frac{2k}{\mu}}\sqrt{\left(\frac{r-r_{0}}{rr_{0}}\right)},
\]

\end_inset

now, because we want 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, we can use 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dt=\frac{dt}{dr}dr,
\]

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int dt=\int\frac{dt}{dr}dr=\int\frac{1}{\left(\frac{dr}{dt}\right)}dr,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\int dt=\int\frac{dt}{dr}dr=\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{\frac{2k}{\mu}}\sqrt{\left(\frac{r-r_{0}}{rr_{0}}\right)}}dr,
\]

\end_inset

so, our goal is to solve the previous integral, but because we want the
 time at which the particles collide, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t=\int_{0}^{t}dt\implies\int_{r_{0}}^{0}dr,
\]

\end_inset

thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t=\int_{r_{0}}^{0}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\frac{2k}{\mu}}\sqrt{\left(\frac{r-r_{0}}{rr_{0}}\right)}}dr,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\int_{r_{0}}^{0}\sqrt{\frac{rr_{0}}{r-r_{0}}}dr,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\int_{r_{0}}^{0}\sqrt{\frac{r_{0}r}{r_{0}\left(\frac{r}{r_{0}}-1\right)}}dr,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\int_{r_{0}}^{0}\sqrt{\frac{r_{0}\frac{r}{r_{0}}}{\left(\frac{r}{r_{0}}-1\right)}}dr
\]

\end_inset

and if we know make the change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=\frac{r}{r_{0}}\implies du=\frac{dr}{r_{0}},
\]

\end_inset

the integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{r_{0}}^{0}\sqrt{\frac{r_{0}\frac{r}{r_{0}}}{\left(\frac{r}{r_{0}}-1\right)}}dr=\int_{1}^{0}r_{0}\sqrt{\frac{r_{0}u}{\left(u-1\right)}}du=\int_{1}^{0}\left(r_{0}\right)^{3/2}\sqrt{\frac{u}{\left(u-1\right)}}du,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\left(r_{0}\right)^{3/2}\int_{1}^{0}\sqrt{\frac{u}{\left(u-1\right)}}du,
\]

\end_inset

now, making another change of variables, this time, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sin^{2}x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $du=2\sin x\cos x$
\end_inset

, and the integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{1}^{0}\sqrt{\frac{u}{\left(u-1\right)}}du=2\int_{\pi/2}^{0}\sin^{2}xdx=2\frac{\pi}{4}=\frac{\pi}{2},
\]

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\left(r_{0}\right)^{3/2}\frac{\pi}{4},
\]

\end_inset

and if we use the calculates 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\left(\frac{k\tau^{2}}{4\pi^{2}\mu}\right)^{1/2}\frac{\pi}{2},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\Delta t=\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{2k}}\sqrt{\frac{k}{\mu}}\left(\frac{\tau}{2\pi}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\Delta t=\frac{\tau}{4\sqrt{2}},
\]

\end_inset

just as we wanted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
